    "author_association": "NONE",
    "body": "### Problem\n\nWhen using BufWritePre to prevent saving an unchanged buffer, the expected behavior is that if the buffer has not been modified, the write should be completely canceled. In Vimscript, checking &modified and throwing an error achieves this reliably. However, in Lua, using vim.bo.modified in a BufWritePre autocmd displays our assertion as expected but does not actually prevent the file from being written, which differs from the Vimscript behavior.\n\nLet's take a look at the Vimscript version:\n\n```vim\nautocmd BufWritePre * if !&modified | throw \"Buffer unchanged\" | endif\n```\n\nIf the buffer hasn’t changed, the write is prevented. This is expected.\n\nAnd when we do the same in Lua:\n\n```lua\nvim.api.nvim_create_autocmd(\"BufWritePre\", {\n    callback = function()\n        if not vim.bo.modified then\n            error(\"Buffer unchanged\")\n        end\n    end,\n})\n```\n\nit displays the error as expected, but the buffer is still written to disk one second later, which is discrepant to Vimscript.\n\n### Steps to reproduce\n\n1. Create a minimal Lua config, `minimal.lua`:\n   ```lua\n   vim.api.nvim_create_autocmd(\"BufWritePre\", {\n       callback = function()\n           if not vim.bo.modified then\n               error(\"Buffer unchanged\")\n           end\n       end,\n   })\n   ```\n2. Open any file with:\n   ```bash\n   nvim --clean -u minimal.lua\n   ```\n3. Try saving an unmodified buffer (`:w`).\n\n### Expected behavior\n\nThe file should not be written if the buffer is unchanged.\n\n### Nvim version (nvim -v)\n\nNVIM v0.11.4\n\n### Vim (not Nvim) behaves the same?\n\nUnable to test since vim doesn't have Lua\n\n### Operating system/version\n\n6.6.87.1-microsoft-standard-WSL2\n\n### Terminal name/version\n\ntty1\n\n### $TERM environment variable\n\nxterm-256color\n\n### Installation\n\nArch Linux Official Repositories",
    "closed_at": null,
    "closed_by": null,
